 12  # Congruence relations
 13  
 14  This file defines congruence relations: equivalence relations that preserve a binary operation,
 15  which in this case is multiplication or addition. The principal definition is a `structure`
 16  extending a `setoid` (an equivalence relation), and the inductive definition of the smallest
 17  congruence relation containing a binary relation is also given (see `con_gen`).
 18  
 19  The file also proves basic properties of the quotient of a type by a congruence relation, and the
 20  complete lattice of congruence relations on a type. We then establish an order-preserving bijection
 21  between the set of congruence relations containing a congruence relation `c` and the set of
 22  congruence relations on the quotient by `c`.
 23  
 24  The second half of the file concerns congruence relations on monoids, in which case the
 25  quotient by the congruence relation is also a monoid. There are results about the universal
 26  property of quotients of monoids, and the isomorphism theorems for monoids.
 27  
 28  ## Implementation notes
 29  
 30  The inductive definition of a congruence relation could be a nested inductive type, defined using
 31  the equivalence closure of a binary relation `eqv_gen`, but the recursor generated does not work.
 32  A nested inductive definition could conceivably shorten proofs, because they would allow invocation
 33  of the corresponding lemmas about `eqv_gen`.
 34  
 35  The lemmas `refl`, `symm` and `trans` are not tagged with `@[refl]`, `@[symm]`, and `@[trans]`
 36  respectively as these tags do not work on a structure coerced to a binary relation.
 37  
 38  There is a coercion from elements of a type to the element's equivalence class under a
 39  congruence relation.
 40  
 41  A congruence relation on a monoid `M` can be thought of as a submonoid of `M × M` for which
 42  membership is an equivalence relation, but whilst this fact is established in the file, it is not
 43  used, since this perspective adds more layers of definitional unfolding.
 44  
 45  ## Tags
 46  
 47  congruence, congruence relation, quotient, quotient by congruence relation, monoid,
 48  quotient monoid, isomorphism theorems
 49  -/
